Patrón Tequila Express carries Mr. DeJoria and his guests around the country on Amtrak's 21,000 miles of routes.</Para><Para>The interior of a 1949 private railcar was renovated with what owner John Webb, head of an insurance brokerage in Fishkill, N.Y., calls a 'retro-modern 1950s diner look.'</Para><Para>Named the Babbling Brook, the car has a working speedometer.</Para><Para>This kitchen was part of a three year, nearly $1 million restoration and renovation project.</Para><Para>Mr. Webb takes his family to California, Washington and Oregon for vacation in the Babbling Brook.</Para><Para>John Webb, 10, reads in a bedroom with bunk beds inside his father's private railcar.</Para><Para>Caitlin Webb, age 8, inside the hallway of a private railcar owned by her father.</Para><Para>Mr. Webb says his children, Caitlin and John, like taking the train on vacations because they wake up somewhere different every day.</Para><Para>The Babbling Brook is one of six private railcars Mr. Webb owns.</Para><Para>The Dearing is a 1925 Pullman, with an observation lounge, dining room, three bedrooms and three bathrooms.</Para><Para>Owner Borden Black runs trips on the Dearing, charging $6,600 a bedroom for a 10-day round trip from Washington to New Orleans.</Para><Para>Ms. Black does the cooking herself on trips. Here she makes creme brûlée french toast.</Para><Para>Diana Bowman of Ann Arbor, Mich., Ken Sherman of Lake Jackson, Texas, Bob LaJeunesse of Ann Arbor, Mich., and Frank Ahouse of Albany, Georgia, sit down for breakfast in the dining room of the Dearing.</Para><Para>Ms. Black says it took six years to bring the Dearing up to the standards necessary to ride along with Amtrak.</Para><Para>Owning a private railcar that takes guests on trips is 'like owning a B&amp;B' says Ms. Black.</Para><Para>There currently are about 150 private railcars (also called 'varnish') in good enough shape to be certified to run attached to Amtrak trains in the U.S., according to the American Association of Private Railroad Car Owners.</Para><Para>To travel, owners pay Amtrak $2.90 per mile, plus additional fees for services. In November, Amtrak's office of inspector general initiated an audit of its private railcar services.</Para><Para>The Dearing at Union Station in Washington, D.C.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field"></Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-look-inside-luxurious-private-railcars-1521727201" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

